{
  "What are the two types of particles in a nucleus?": "",
  "Protons and neutrons": "",
  "Photons and neutrons": "",
  "Electrons and protons": "",
  "Quarks and leptons": "",
  "Neutrons are neutral (uncharged) subatomic particles in the nucleus. Isotopes of an element differ in the number of neutrons, which affects mass but not chemical properties. The answer is 'Protons and neutrons'. The other options — 'Electrons and protons', 'Quarks and leptons', and 'Photons and neutrons' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is the atomic number Z?": "",
  "The number of protons": "",
  "The total nucleons": "",
  "The number of electrons in an ion": "",
  "The number of neutrons": "",
  "The atomic number (Z) equals the number of protons in the nucleus. It defines the element's identity and determines its position on the periodic table. The answer is 'The number of protons'. The other options — 'The number of neutrons', 'The total nucleons', and 'The number of electrons in an ion' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What are isotopes?": "",
  "Different elements with same mass": "",
  "Atoms with no neutrons": "",
  "Atoms with the same Z but different neutrons": "",
  "Atoms with different Z": "",
  "Isotopes are atoms of the same element with different numbers of neutrons (same atomic number, different mass number). They have identical chemical properties but different masses. The answer is 'Atoms with the same Z but different neutrons'. The other options — 'Atoms with different Z', 'Atoms with no neutrons', and 'Different elements with same mass' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is alpha decay?": "",
  "Emission of a neutron": "",
  "Emission of an electron": "",
  "Emission of a photon": "",
  "Emission of a ⁴₂He nucleus; Z decreases by 2, A by 4": "",
  "Alpha particles (⁴₂He) are heavy (+2 charge) and can be stopped by paper or skin. In alpha decay, the parent loses 2 protons and 2 neutrons (atomic number -2, mass number -4). The answer is 'Emission of a ⁴₂He nucleus; Z decreases by 2, A by 4'. The other options — 'Emission of an electron', 'Emission of a photon', and 'Emission of a neutron' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is half-life?": "",
  "Time for all nuclei to decay": "",
  "Time for one nucleus to form": "",
  "Time for half the radioactive nuclei to decay": "",
  "Time for radiation to stop": "",
  "Half-life is the time for half the substance to decay/react. After n half-lives, the remaining amount = initial × (1/2)ⁿ. The answer is Time for half the radioactive nuclei to decay. The other options — 'Time for all nuclei to decay', 'Time for one nucleus to form', and 'Time for radiation to stop' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is nuclear fission?": "",
  "Radioactive decay only": "",
  "Any nuclear reaction": "",
  "A heavy nucleus splitting into lighter nuclei": "",
  "Light nuclei combining": "",
  "Nuclear fission splits a heavy nucleus (like uranium-235) into lighter nuclei, releasing neutrons and energy. A chain reaction occurs when released neutrons trigger more fissions. The answer is 'A heavy nucleus splitting into lighter nuclei'. The other options — 'Light nuclei combining', 'Any nuclear reaction', and 'Radioactive decay only' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is nuclear fusion?": "",
  "Light nuclei combining into a heavier nucleus": "",
  "Electron capture": "",
  "Chemical bonding": "",
  "Heavy nuclei splitting": "",
  "Nuclear fusion combines light nuclei (like hydrogen) into heavier ones, releasing energy. It requires extremely high temperatures (millions of degrees) to overcome electrostatic repulsion. The answer is 'Light nuclei combining into a heavier nucleus'. The other options — 'Heavy nuclei splitting', 'Chemical bonding', and 'Electron capture' — are related concepts but do not correctly answer this specific question.": "",
  "What is beta decay?": "",
  "A neutron in the nucleus converts into a proton and emits an electron": "",
  "The nucleus ejects two protons and two neutrons as a single particle": "",
  "The nucleus emits a high-energy photon without changing its composition": "",
  "An electron in the atom's outermost shell is absorbed by the nucleus": "",
  "In beta-minus decay, a neutron inside the nucleus converts into a proton, emitting an electron (beta particle) and an antineutrino. The atomic number increases by 1 while the mass number stays the same.": "",
  "What is gamma radiation?": "",
  "A stream of fast-moving helium nuclei emitted from an unstable atom": "",
  "High-energy electromagnetic radiation emitted from an excited nucleus": "",
  "A stream of electrons released during chemical reactions in metals": "",
  "Low-energy radio waves emitted by all radioactive materials at rest": "",
  "Gamma rays are high-energy photons (electromagnetic radiation) emitted from the nucleus when it transitions from a higher energy state to a lower one. Unlike alpha and beta decay, gamma emission does not change the atomic number or mass number.": "",
  "What is the mass number (A) of an atom?": "",
  "The total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus": "",
  "The total number of electrons orbiting the nucleus of the atom": "",
  "The number of protons minus the number of neutrons in the atom": "",
  "The mass of one atom measured in kilograms on a laboratory scale": "",
  "The mass number A is the total number of nucleons (protons + neutrons) in the nucleus. It is always a whole number. The relationship is A = Z + N, where Z is the atomic number (protons) and N is the number of neutrons.": "",
  "What is a nucleon?": "",
  "Any particle that orbits outside the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "A proton or neutron found inside the nucleus of an atom": "",
  "A photon that is emitted during gamma radiation from a nucleus": "",
  "An electron that has been captured by the nucleus during decay": "",
  "A nucleon is a collective term for the particles found inside the nucleus: protons and neutrons. The mass number A counts the total number of nucleons in the nucleus.": "",
  "Define the term 'radioactive decay' in nuclear physics.": "",
  "The spontaneous emission of particles or energy from an unstable nucleus": "",
  "The chemical breakdown of a molecule into its individual atoms": "",
  "The gradual loss of electrons from a metal exposed to strong light": "",
  "The absorption of neutrons by a stable nucleus during bombardment": "",
  "Radioactive decay is the spontaneous and random process by which an unstable atomic nucleus loses energy by emitting radiation in the form of particles (alpha, beta) or electromagnetic waves (gamma rays). It transforms the parent nucleus into a daughter nucleus.": "",
  "What is meant by 'chain reaction' in the context of nuclear fission?": "",
  "A series of chemical reactions that produce heat in a conventional furnace": "",
  "A process where neutrons from one fission event trigger additional fission events": "",
  "A reaction where two light nuclei combine repeatedly to form heavier elements": "",
  "A sequence of gamma ray emissions from a single unstable radioactive nucleus": "",
  "In a chain reaction, the neutrons released from the fission of one heavy nucleus strike other heavy nuclei and cause them to undergo fission as well, releasing more neutrons. This self-sustaining process is what powers nuclear reactors and nuclear weapons.": "",
  "What does the term 'binding energy' mean in nuclear physics?": "",
  "The energy needed to disassemble a nucleus into its individual protons and neutrons": "",
  "The energy released when an electron is added to a neutral atom in its ground state": "",
  "The energy required to move an atom from a solid state to a gas state": "",
  "The kinetic energy of a neutron traveling at the speed of light through space": "",
  "Nuclear binding energy is the energy required to completely separate all protons and neutrons in a nucleus. It represents the energy equivalent of the mass defect (the difference between the mass of separated nucleons and the mass of the assembled nucleus).": "",
  "What is 'mass defect' in nuclear physics?": "",
  "The difference between the mass of separated nucleons and the actual nuclear mass": "",
  "The loss of mass that occurs when an atom loses all of its electrons": "",
  "An error in measuring atomic mass caused by imprecise laboratory equipment": "",
  "The mass gained by a nucleus when it absorbs a high-energy gamma photon": "",
  "Mass defect is the difference between the sum of the masses of individual protons and neutrons and the actual mass of the assembled nucleus. This 'missing' mass has been converted to binding energy according to E = mc², which holds the nucleus together.": "",
  "Define 'critical mass' as used in nuclear physics.": "",
  "The minimum amount of fissile material needed to sustain a chain reaction": "",
  "The maximum mass a star can have before collapsing into a black hole": "",
  "The total mass of all radioactive waste produced by a nuclear reactor": "",
  "The mass of a single uranium atom before it undergoes fission reaction": "",
  "Critical mass is the minimum amount of fissile material (such as uranium-235 or plutonium-239) needed so that enough neutrons from each fission event go on to cause at least one more fission, sustaining a chain reaction.": "",
  "What is an 'alpha particle'?": "",
  "A high-speed electron emitted from a nucleus during beta decay processes": "",
  "A helium-4 nucleus consisting of two protons and two neutrons": "",
  "A high-energy photon emitted from an excited nucleus after beta decay": "",
  "A neutral particle with no charge emitted alongside beta particles": "",
  "An alpha particle is a helium-4 nucleus (⁴₂He) made of 2 protons and 2 neutrons. It has a charge of +2 and is relatively heavy. Alpha particles are the least penetrating form of radiation and can be stopped by a sheet of paper or human skin.": "",
  "What does the term 'strong nuclear force' refer to?": "",
  "The gravitational attraction between protons and neutrons in the nucleus": "",
  "The force that holds protons and neutrons together inside the nucleus": "",
  "The electromagnetic repulsion between electrons in different energy levels": "",
  "The weak force responsible for beta decay in unstable atomic nuclei": "",
  "The strong nuclear force is the fundamental force that holds protons and neutrons together in the nucleus. It operates at very short range (about 10⁻¹⁵ m) and is strong enough to overcome the electromagnetic repulsion between positively charged protons.": "",
  "What is a 'daughter nucleus' in radioactive decay?": "",
  "The original unstable nucleus before it undergoes radioactive decay": "",
  "The new nucleus formed after a parent nucleus undergoes radioactive decay": "",
  "A nucleus that has absorbed a neutron and become temporarily stable": "",
  "Any nucleus that contains an equal number of protons and neutrons": "",
  "When a radioactive 'parent' nucleus undergoes decay, the resulting nucleus is called the 'daughter' nucleus. For example, when uranium-238 undergoes alpha decay, the daughter nucleus is thorium-234.": "",
  "Define 'nuclear energy' as it relates to fission and fusion.": "",
  "Energy stored in chemical bonds between atoms in a nuclear fuel molecule": "",
  "Energy released from changes in the binding energy of atomic nuclei": "",
  "Thermal energy produced by friction between atoms inside a reactor core": "",
  "Electrical energy generated by electrons moving through a power grid": "",
  "Nuclear energy is the energy released when atomic nuclei undergo changes — either splitting apart (fission) or combining (fusion). This energy comes from the conversion of mass to energy (E = mc²) as the products have greater binding energy per nucleon than the reactants.": "",
  "A sample of a radioactive isotope has a half-life of 10 years. If a scientist starts with 80 grams, how much of the original isotope remains after 30 years?": "",
  "40 grams": "",
  "20 grams": "",
  "10 grams": "",
  "5 grams": "",
  "After 30 years, the sample has gone through 3 half-lives (30/10 = 3). After each half-life, half the material remains: 80 → 40 → 20 → 10 grams. So 10 grams remain after 30 years.": "",
  "A nuclear power plant uses uranium-235 as fuel. A student asks why the uranium must be enriched (concentrated) before use. What is the best explanation?": "",
  "Natural uranium does not contain enough U-235 to sustain a chain reaction efficiently": "",
  "Natural uranium is too radioactive to handle safely in any reactor facility": "",
  "Enrichment removes all the neutrons so fission can proceed more quickly": "",
  "Enrichment converts uranium into plutonium, which is the actual reactor fuel": "",
  "Natural uranium is mostly U-238 (about 99.3%) with only about 0.7% U-235. Since U-235 is the isotope that readily undergoes fission, enrichment increases its concentration so that enough fission events occur to sustain a controlled chain reaction.": "",
  "A student learns that the Sun produces energy through nuclear fusion. She wonders why scientists cannot easily replicate fusion on Earth. What is the primary challenge?": "",
  "Fusion requires extremely high temperatures to overcome the electrostatic repulsion between nuclei": "",
  "Fusion only works with elements heavier than iron, which are rare on Earth": "",
  "There is not enough hydrogen on Earth to sustain a fusion reaction at all": "",
  "Fusion produces no energy on Earth because gravity is too weak here": "",
  "Fusion requires temperatures of millions of degrees so that hydrogen nuclei (both positively charged) move fast enough to overcome their electrostatic repulsion and get close enough for the strong nuclear force to bind them. Containing plasma at such temperatures is the main engineering challenge.": "",
  "A lab technician uses three different materials to test which can stop each type of radiation. She finds that alpha particles are stopped by paper, beta particles by aluminum foil, and gamma rays require thick lead. What does this tell her about the penetrating power of these radiations?": "",
  "Alpha is most penetrating, followed by beta, then gamma is least penetrating": "",
  "Gamma is most penetrating, followed by beta, then alpha is least penetrating": "",
  "All three types of radiation have equal penetrating power in all materials": "",
  "Beta is most penetrating, followed by alpha, then gamma is least penetrating": "",
  "The materials needed to stop each type reveal their penetrating power. Alpha particles (heavy, charged) are stopped by paper. Beta particles (lighter, charged electrons) penetrate paper but are stopped by aluminum. Gamma rays (massless photons) are the most penetrating and require thick, dense materials like lead.": "",
  "A student writes the nuclear equation for alpha decay of radium-226 and gets Ra(226,88) → Rn(222,86) + He(4,2). She checks that both sides balance. What two quantities must be conserved?": "",
  "Temperature and pressure must remain equal on both sides": "",
  "Atomic number (Z) and mass number (A) must be conserved": "",
  "Only the mass number needs to be conserved; charge can change freely": "",
  "The number of electrons and photons must be equal on both sides": "",
  "In nuclear equations, both atomic number (total charge/protons) and mass number (total nucleons) must be conserved. Here: Z: 88 = 86 + 2, and A: 226 = 222 + 4, confirming the equation is balanced.": "",
  "An archaeologist uses carbon-14 dating to determine the age of a wooden artifact. She finds that the artifact has one-quarter of the original carbon-14 remaining. If the half-life of carbon-14 is about 5,730 years, approximately how old is the artifact?": "",
  "About 5,730 years old": "",
  "About 11,460 years old": "",
  "About 17,190 years old": "",
  "About 22,920 years old": "",
  "One-quarter remaining means 2 half-lives have passed (1 → 1/2 → 1/4). Two half-lives of carbon-14 = 2 × 5,730 = 11,460 years. So the artifact is approximately 11,460 years old.": "",
  "A doctor uses a radioactive tracer with a short half-life for a medical scan. A student asks why a short half-life is preferred for medical use. What is the best reason?": "",
  "Short half-life tracers are cheaper to produce in a standard chemistry lab": "",
  "Short half-life tracers produce brighter images on all types of medical scans": "",
  "The radioactivity decreases quickly, reducing the patient's total radiation exposure": "",
  "Short half-life materials emit only alpha particles, which are safest for patients": "",
  "A short half-life means the tracer decays quickly, so the patient is exposed to radiation for only a brief period. This minimizes the total dose and reduces potential harm, while still providing enough time to complete the diagnostic imaging.": "",
  "A student reads that nuclear fission of 1 kg of uranium-235 releases about 80 terajoules of energy, while burning 1 kg of coal releases about 24 megajoules. What does this comparison illustrate?": "",
  "Coal is a more efficient energy source than uranium for generating electricity": "",
  "Nuclear reactions release vastly more energy per unit mass than chemical reactions": "",
  "Chemical reactions and nuclear reactions release approximately the same energy": "",
  "Burning coal produces nuclear energy through a hidden fission process inside it": "",
  "Nuclear fission releases millions of times more energy per kilogram than chemical combustion. This is because nuclear reactions involve changes in nuclear binding energy (E = mc²), while chemical reactions only involve rearranging electron bonds, which store far less energy.": "",
  "A student is studying control rods in a nuclear reactor. She learns that control rods are made of materials like cadmium that absorb neutrons. Why is absorbing neutrons important for reactor safety?": "",
  "Absorbing neutrons prevents the fuel from becoming radioactive in the first place": "",
  "Absorbing neutrons controls the rate of the chain reaction to prevent meltdown": "",
  "Absorbing neutrons converts them into energy that powers the cooling systems": "",
  "Absorbing neutrons changes uranium into a non-radioactive form of the element": "",
  "Control rods absorb excess neutrons to regulate the fission chain reaction. By inserting or withdrawing control rods, operators can control how many neutrons go on to cause further fission events. This prevents the reaction from accelerating uncontrollably.": "",
  "A student compares fission and fusion and notes that both release energy. She asks why fusion is considered a potential future energy source if fission already works. What is the main advantage of fusion over fission?": "",
  "Fusion uses abundant hydrogen fuel and produces minimal long-lived radioactive waste": "",
  "Fusion is already widely used in power plants around the world today": "",
  "Fusion requires no energy input to start and maintains itself without heating": "",
  "Fusion produces more radioactive waste but generates far less energy per reaction": "",
  "Fusion's main advantages are that its fuel (hydrogen isotopes like deuterium) is virtually unlimited from seawater, and the primary byproduct is helium — a non-radioactive, non-toxic gas. Unlike fission, fusion does not produce long-lived radioactive waste or carry the risk of nuclear meltdown.": ""
}